translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah was sitting at her desk."
    new "Sarah was sitting at her desk."

    old "In front of her were a series of books on the subjects of political philosophy."
    new "In front of her were a series of books on the subjects of political philosophy."

    old "Sarah had read her share, growing up in Castle Reinmeer."
    new "Sarah had read her share, growing up in Castle Reinmeer."

    old "Still, she felt wholly unprepared for the question before her."
    new "Still, she felt wholly unprepared for the question before her."

    old "Rosanna had always balanced the interests of the nobility and commonfolk."
    new "Rosanna had always balanced the interests of the nobility and commonfolk."

    old "It was a balance that had worked well enough over the centuries to maintain a peace."
    new "It was a balance that had worked well enough over the centuries to maintain a peace."

    old "Marion's uprising had shattered that fact."
    new "Marion's uprising had shattered that fact."

    old "The truth was that the nobility was now weaker than it had ever been."
    new "The truth was that the nobility was now weaker than it had ever been."

    old "In part, Sarah appreciated that fact."
    new "In part, Sarah appreciated that fact."

    old "Difficult questions, long held off by the entrenched powers, were suddenly up for debate."
    new "Difficult questions, long held off by the entrenched powers, were suddenly up for debate."

    old "The increased social mobility of the commonfolk had motivated many to develop new industries, adding to the prosperity of her nation."
    new "The increased social mobility of the commonfolk had motivated many to develop new industries, adding to the prosperity of her nation."

    old "Yet..."
    new "Yet..."

    old "Sarah also knew the dangers of antagonizing the nobility."
    new "Sarah also knew the dangers of antagonizing the nobility."

    old "In defending her country from the Tribes, she had been too short-sighted in considering the interests of the Old Houses."
    new "In defending her country from the Tribes, she had been too short-sighted in considering the interests of the Old Houses."

    old "In turn, thousands had died in the fighting."
    new "In turn, thousands had died in the fighting."

    old "Sarah did not want to risk such a tragedy again."
    new "Sarah did not want to risk such a tragedy again."

    old "She began to consider."
    new "She began to consider."

    old "Support the nobility"
    new "Support the nobility"

    old "Sarah knew that the best option would be to side with the nobility."
    new "Sarah knew that the best option would be to side with the nobility."

    old "Her country had been nearly torn apart by neglecting them once. She would not make that mistake again."
    new "Her country had been nearly torn apart by neglecting them once. She would not make that mistake again."

    old "And would it not also be better for the common folk, if she could thus prevent more bloodshed?"
    new "And would it not also be better for the common folk, if she could thus prevent more bloodshed?"

    old "Whichever would come to pass, she would have to make certain that the new political decree would favor the nobles."
    new "Whichever would come to pass, she would have to make certain that the new political decree would favor the nobles."

    old "Support the commoners"
    new "Support the commoners"

    old "Sarah knew in her heart that could be loyal to only the common folk."
    new "Sarah knew in her heart that could be loyal to only the common folk."

    old "They were the true heart of her nation. The people that she was tasking with ruling."
    new "They were the true heart of her nation. The people that she was tasking with ruling."

    old "It was more than simply a desire. It was her divine obligation."
    new "It was more than simply a desire. It was her divine obligation."

    old "Just as it had once been her Father's task."
    new "Just as it had once been her Father's task."

    old "Whichever would come to pass, she would have to make certain that the new political decree would favor the commoners."
    new "Whichever would come to pass, she would have to make certain that the new political decree would favor the commoners."

